05317nam a22007575i 9780226662428DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019012199  a97802266624287 a10.7208/97802266624282doi  a(DE-B1597)545039  a(OCoLC)1120693520  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJV8138b.C837 2019 4aJV8138b.C837 2020 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.4841209452231 aCvajner, Martina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSoviet Signoras :bPersonal and Collective Transformations in Eastern European Migration /cMartina Cvajner. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1 halftone, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFieldwork Encounters and Discoveries00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Room of One’s Own: Managing Spaces, Lives, and Laws in Residential Care Work -- t2. Practicing Abundance: Immigrant Women and the Challenge of Consumption -- t3. Strong Mothers, Great Lovers: Sexuality in Emigration -- t4. Getting Serious: Courtship, Love, and (Maybe) Marriage in Emigration -- t5. Proper, Respectable Places: The Arduous Construction of Community Institutions -- tConclusion: From the Detritus of the Soviet Union into a New Social World -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: How I Conducted My Study -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex of Participant Pseudonyms -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the Western world, the air is filled with talk of immigration. The changes brought by immigration have triggered a renewed fervor for isolationism able to shutter political traditions and party systems. So often absent from these conversations on migration are however the actual stories and experiences of the migrants themselves. In fact, migration does not simply transport people. It also changes them deeply. Enter Martina Cvajner’s Soviet Signoras, a far-reaching ethnographic study of two decades in the lives of women who migrated to northern Italy from several former Soviet republics. Cvajner details the personal and collective changes brought about by the experience of migration for these women: from the first hours arriving in a new country with no friends, relatives, or existing support networks, to later remaking themselves for their new environment. In response to their traumatic displacement, the women of Soviet Signoras—nearly all of whom found work in their new Western homes as elder care givers—refashioned themselves in highly sexualized, materialistic, and intentionally conspicuous ways. Cvajner’s focus on overt sexuality and materialism is far from sensationalist, though. By zeroing in on these elements of personal identity, she reveals previously unexplored sides of the social psychology of migration, coloring our contemporary discussion with complex shades of humanity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zItaly. 0aWomen foreign workerszItaly. 0aWomen immigrantszItalyxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aEastern Europe.  acare work.  agender.  ahyperfemininity.  aimmigrant associations.  ainternational migration.  aintimacy.  amigrant pioneers.  apost Soviet migration.  asexuality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2